IncidentSuppNarrative.NarrativeText:
MSP marked vehicle V-11 is equipped with a mobile recording device
 
Defendant: Caroline Grace Owens
Driver license #: VA C66049582
Date of Birth: 3/13/2000
Date of Arrest: 2/17/23
Time of Arrest: 0004
DUI #: 23-96-037
PBT Results: Refused
Intoximeter Results: Refused
 Subsequent Offender: NO

CERTIFICATES AND TRAINING
-Trained in administering standardized field sobriety tests through the Maryland State Police and National Highway Traffic Safety Administration
 
VEHICLE IN MOTION (PHASE 1)
On February 17, 2022, at approximately 2346 hours, Trooper First Class C. Shubert #7062 with the Maryland State Police Berlin, was on-duty operating V-11 in the area of N Baltimore Ave and 29th St, Ocean City, Worcester County, Maryland 21842. At that time I was traveling northbound on N Baltimore Ave in lane one when I observed in front of me traveling in lane one a Tan Chevy Colorado bearing Virginia registration (TWV4763) that had crossed the white dotted line into lane two by a tire width three times. The vehicle then made a left turn onto Philadelphia Ave and a right turn onto 32nd St. I then activated my emergency equipment and conducted a traffic stop on the vehicle.

 PERSONAL CONTACT (PHASE 2)
I exited my patrol vehicle and made contact with the driver and advised her why she was being stopped. While speaking with the driver I detected the strong odor of an alcoholic beverage emitting from the drivers breath and person and bloodshot and glassy eyes, slurred speech. I asked the driver for her license and registration. The driver handed me her license and I identified her as Caroline Grace Owens (W/F, 3/13/2000) through her Virginia license. I asked Owens how many alcoholic beverages she consumed prior to driving to which she advised “1 beer”. I then returned to my patrol vehicle to conduct routine MVA checks, once completing MVA checks, I returned to Owens vehicle and asked her to step out and walk to the front of her vehicle to conduct the standardized field sobriety test and to continue my investigation to which she consented. While at the front of her vehicle I continued to smell the strong odor of an alcoholic beverage emitting from her breath and person. I asked Owens how many alcoholic beverages she consumed prior to driving to which she advised “2 beers”. I asked her what type of alcoholic beverages she consumed prior to driving to which she advised “Miller light”.

PRE-ARREST SCREENING (PHASE 3)
The evaluation was performed on 32nd St where Owens vehicle made a complete stop. The surface was level and free from any obvious debris. The weather was clear and approximately 43 degrees. Owens appeared to be in good physical condition and did not display any visible injuries. My front emergency lights were deactivated during all tests.
 
I asked Owens the following questions:
Glasses- NO
Medication- NO
Physical disabilities-NO
 
HORIZONTAL GAZE NYSTAGMUS (_6_/_6_ clues observed)
The first test given was the Horizontal Gaze Nystagmus test. A black and gray pen was used as the tests stimulus and held approximately 12-15 inches from Owens eyes. She was instructed to look straight ahead, keeping her head still while following and focusing on the tip of the stimulus with her eyes until told to stop. Her pupils were equal in size and showed equal tracking. She was positioned in a manner to ensure the headlights of passing traffic would not interfere with the test results. I asked if she understood the instructions, and she stated “Yes”.
 1.  Lack of Smooth Pursuit - Present in both eyes
2. Distinct and Sustained Nystagmus at Maximum Deviation - Present in both eyes
3. Onset of Nystagmus Prior to 45 Degrees - Present in both eyes
***While conducting the test Owens advised “I swear I'm not that drunk”.

 
WALK AND TURN (_7_/_8_ clues observed)
Prior to Owens performing the test, I properly explained and demonstrated how the test should be conducted. She was instructed to place her right foot directly in front of her left foot and touch heel to toe. She was instructed and demonstrated to place her hands flat to her side and to remain in the position until told to begin. She was advised to take nine (9) steps on a straight-line touching heel to toe on every step. She was to keep her hands flat to her sides, keep her eyes focused on her feet, and count every step aloud. On the ninth step, I explained and demonstrated for Owens to keep her lead foot on the line, and to take a series of small steps around with her lead foot to turn completely around. I again explained and demonstrated the second series of nine (9) steps was to be performed identically to the first series. Owens was instructed that once she began the test that she was not to stop walking until the test was complete, keep her hands down by her sides, look down at her feet, and count each step out loud. I asked Owens if she understood the test, and she stated "Yes". 
Instructional Stage:
1). Broke heel to toe contact more than an inch in an attempt to maintain balance
2). Started the test prior being told to begin the test
Walking stage (1st Nine):
1). Stepped off of the line more than an inch on steps 3,5,7,8
2). Missed heel to toe contact more than half an inch on step 6,9
3). Took 17 steps instead on nine as demonstrated

Walking stage (2nd Nine):
1). Missed heel to toe contact more than half an inch on steps 2
2). Stopped walking after taking step #2
Turn:
1). Turned without keeping the lead foot planted


ONE LEG STAND (_3_/_4 clues observed)
Prior to Owens performing the test, I properly explained and demonstrated how the test should be conducted. She was instructed to stand with her heels together and hands down by her sides while the instructions were given and during the test. When instructed to start, Owens was to raise the foot of her choice off the ground approximately 6 inches. While her leg was raised she was to keep her leg straight, watch her raised foot, and count out loud by thousands (one thousand one, one thousand-two), and to continue the test until told to stop. I asked Owens if she understood the test, and she stated "Yes”. 
Right foot
Seconds 0-10:
1). Swaying from left to right more than six inches on second 6
2). Put foot down on second 8
3). Raised arms more than six inches away from body on second 9
Seconds 11-20:
Did  not conduct
Seconds 21-30:
Did  not conduct
 
Additional field test:
 (1).  I asked Owens if she knew the English alphabet to which she advised “Yes”.  I asked her if she could start at the letter “H”. And go to the letter “T”. Without singing the alphabet to which she advised “Yes”. Owens started at the letter H and stopped at Z.
 (2). I then asked Owens if she could count backwards from 57 to 36 to which she stated “Yes”. Owens counted from 57 to 34 and stopped.


 
 Owens had the opportunity to take a preliminary breath test. Owens refused to a preliminary breath test.
ARREST:
Based on the following, I had reason to believe Owens was driving a motor vehicle under the influence of alcohol:
 * Driving behavior
*Admitting to consuming alcohol
*My observed signs of impairment

At approximately 0004 hours, I placed Owens under arrest for driving under the influence of alcohol. I later checked her mouth for any foreign objects and did not locate any. Owens was placed in the front passenger seat of my patrol vehicle. While on-scene I played the English audio version of the DR-15 Advice of Rights form to Owens via the MVA official website with a paper copy in front of her to read. At the conclusion of the DR-15 form, I verbally repeated the possible suspensions and sanctions that can be imposed by the MVA per the DR-15 form. Owens refused the Intoximeter test and signed the same at approximately 0038 hours.
Alcohol Concentration Test Result: Refused. 

Owens was later released to a sober adult. Owens received pertinent copies of paperwork.
Owens was charged with the following:
21-902 (A1i) Driving motor vehicle while under the influence of alcohol
21-902 (B1i) Driving vehicle while impaired by alcohol
21-301 (A) Failure to drive vehicle on right half of roadway when required

All events occurred in Worcester County, Maryland.
Case closed.
